                </FooterDetails>
                <MainParagraph/>
                <PointOfContact/>
                <ProgramName>ESTABLISHMENT AND ORGANIZATION</ProgramName>
                <Activity ProgramAndActivitiesId="177" SortOrder="1">
                    <Heading/>
                    <Details>
                        <Detail SortOrder="1" TypeOfProgramAndActivitiesDetailsId="248">
                            <FooterDetails>
                                <Email/>
                                <Footer/>
                                <WebAddress>https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/STATUTE-81/pdf/STATUTE-81-Pg664.pdf</WebAddress>
                            </FooterDetails>
                            <Heading/>
                            <Paragraph>On December 20, 1967, President Lyndon B. Johnson approved
                                Public Law 90–219, "an act to provide for the establishment of a
                                Federal Judicial Center [FJC], and for other purposes." The FJC was
                                established "to further the development and adoption of improved
                                judicial administration in the courts of the United States" (81
                                Stat. 664).</Paragraph>
                        </Detail>
                        <Detail SortOrder="2" TypeOfProgramAndActivitiesDetailsId="2739">
                            <FooterDetails>
                                <Email/>
                                <Footer/>
                                <WebAddress>https://uscode.house.gov/browse/prelim@title28/part3/chapter42&amp;edition=prelim</WebAddress>
                            </FooterDetails>
                            <Heading/>
                            <Paragraph>The FJC's statutory duties are described in chapter 42,
                                sections 620–629, of 28 U.S.C.</Paragraph>
                        </Detail>
                        <Detail SortOrder="3" TypeOfProgramAndActivitiesDetailsId="254">
                            <FooterDetails>
                                <Email/>
                                <Footer/>
                                <WebAddress>https://www.fjc.gov/about/statute</WebAddress>
                            </FooterDetails>
                            <Heading/>
                            <Paragraph>The Board of the FJC determines the agency's basic policies
                                and activities. The Board comprises the Chief Justice of the United
                                States, who permanently chairs of the Board by statute; two circuit
                                judges of the U.S. courts of appeals; three judges of the U.S.
                                district courts; one bankruptcy judge; and one magistrate judge. The
                                Judicial Conference of the United States elects these eight members
                                of the Board for 4-year terms. The ninth member is the Director of
                                the Administrative Office of the United States Courts, who serves on
                                Board in a permanent capacity. An elected member may serve only for
                                one four-year term on the Board.</Paragraph>
                        </Detail>
                        <Detail SortOrder="4" TypeOfProgramAndActivitiesDetailsId="2740">
                            <FooterDetails>
                                <Email/>
                                <Footer/>
                                <WebAddress/>
                            </FooterDetails>
                            <Heading/>
                            <Paragraph>The FJC does not post an organizational chart on its
                                website.</Paragraph>
                        </Detail>
                    </Details>
                </Activity>
            </ProgramAndActivity>
            <ProgramAndActivity ProgramAndActivitiesId="530" SortOrder="2">
                <FooterDetails>
                    <Email/>
                    <Footer/>
                    <WebAddress/>
